	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and Kennedy Space Center Director Jim Kennedy will speak March 12, to nearly 1,000 high school students competing in a high-energy robotics contest at UCF.    Bush and Kennedy will address a luncheon crowd of about 100 business and education leaders in the UCF Arena skybox before heading to the arena floor to talk briefly with students in the FIRST Robotics Florida regional competition. During the competition, robots designed, built and programmed by students with help from corporate mentors in the last six weeks will pass balls to human players and hang from 10-foot-high bars.    The invitation-only luncheon, where Kennedy plans to speak about the space shuttles return to flight, will begin at 11:30 a.m. on Friday. Bush and Kennedy are scheduled to speak with the students at about 1 p.m. The competition, designed to better prepare students for careers in science and technology, is free and open to the public.  
		
	
		
			The FIRST (For Inspiration and Recognition of Science and Technology) Robotics competition will begin Thursday with practice sessions and conclude with an awards ceremony Saturday afternoon. The event will feature 42 teams, many of which represent Central Florida schools. Squads from Georgia, Massachusetts, New York, North Dakota, South Carolina and Puerto Rico also will compete.    "FIRST Robotics provides high school students with an exceptional, hands-on education in science and technology that prepares them well for high-tech, high-wage jobs," Bush said. "The efforts of FIRST Robotics and the companies that mentor and sponsor the competitors help to strengthen and diversify Floridas economy, as companies with high-tech jobs are much more likely to come to our state if we can show that our work force is well-educated and well-prepared."  
		
	
		
			Guests who plan to attend the luncheon, which is sponsored by Progress Energy, include the superintendents of schools in Brevard, Orange, Osceola and Seminole counties. Top executives from companies such as Lockheed Martin, the Boeing Co., Harris Corp. and SunTrust also will attend.    More than 23,000 students from the United States, Canada, Brazil and the United Kingdom are expected to participate in 27 FIRST Robotics competitions this year. While they learn a lot from participating, they also have fun. Many teams wear costumes, and music blares throughout the arena during the event.    Atlanta will host the FIRST Robotics national championships in April. UCF and NASA/Kennedy Space Center are co-hosts of the Florida regional competition.    "The FIRST competition is a special event allowing Americas future scientists and engineers to show off their talents," Kennedy said. "NASA is proud to be a part of the competition as these are the people who will carry out President George W. Bushs new human space exploration vision in the years to come."     For six weeks before the event, competitors design, build and learn to operate the robots and gain experience in marketing and budgets. Mentors from Kennedy Space Center and corporations such as Motorola, Siemens and Lockheed Martin work with the competitors, and students from UCF and other universities also help them.  "Its very important that we start early and give kids in school a strong base in science and technology," said Erik Halleus, a retired vice president with Siemens Corp. and chairman of the FIRST Robotics regional planning committee. "(FIRST competitors) have an understanding of project management. They have an understanding of software and hardware. When they get into a university, they are far ahead of everyone else. The experience of being on a robotics team broadens their horizons and gives them new insights."    For more information on the competition and a full schedule of events this weekend, go to www.firstfloridaregional.org.    
		
	
